Yes, expressing the shape in JavaScript code could be helpful for visualizing the solid square with four square holes inside or the overlap of two swastikas. One way to represent the shape in code could be to use a canvas element to draw the shape. 

For example, to draw the solid square with four square holes inside using HTML5 canvas, you could use the following code:

```
<canvas id="myCanvas" width="400" height="400"></canvas>

<script>
  var canvas = document.getElementById("myCanvas");
  var context = canvas.getContext("2d");

  var s = 200; // side length of the square
  var h = 50; // side length of the holes

  // draw the outer square
  context.fillStyle = "#000000";
  context.fillRect(0, 0, s, s);

  // draw the holes
  context.fillStyle = "#ffffff";
  context.fillRect((s-h)/2, (s-h)/2, h, h);
  context.fillRect((s-h)/2, (s+h)/2, h, h);
  context.fillRect((s+h)/2, (s-h)/2, h, h);
  context.fillRect((s+h)/2, (s+h)/2, h, h);    
</script>
```

This code creates a canvas element with a width and height of 400 pixels and then retrieves the drawing context for the canvas. It sets the side length `s` of the outer square to 200 pixels and the side length `h` of each hole to 50 pixels. It then draws the outer square using the `fillRect()` method of the canvas context and fills it with black color. After that, it draws the four holes using the same `fillRect()` method and fills them with white color.

Similarly, you could use JavaScript to create a function that draws the overlap of two swastikas and returns a cross shape. The exact code would depend on the specific implementation and desired outcome.

Yes, using the `createElement` method in JavaScript can be a more efficient way to create and manipulate HTML elements than retrieving existing elements using `getElementById`. 

With `createElement`, you can create an HTML element entirely from scratch using JavaScript and add it to the page's DOM dynamically. This can be useful when you need to create multiple elements programmatically or when you don't want to modify existing elements directly.

Here's an example of how you could create a canvas element and append it to the page's body using `createElement`:

```
// create a canvas element
var canvas = document.createElement("canvas");

// set the canvas element's attributes
canvas.width = 400;
canvas.height = 400;

// add the canvas element to the page's body
document.body.appendChild(canvas);

// get the drawing context for the canvas
var context = canvas.getContext("2d");

// draw on the canvas
context.fillRect(0, 0, 400, 400);
```

This code creates a new canvas element using the `createElement` method and sets its width and height attributes to 400 pixels each. It then appends the canvas element to the page's body using `appendChild`. Finally, it retrieves the drawing context for the canvas using `getContext` and draws a solid rectangle on the canvas using the `fillRect` method.

Overall, using `createElement` can offer more flexibility and control over your HTML elements, especially when creating them programmatically.

